    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2007810559" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2007810559" />
    <a title="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur"><img alt="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602184090p2/16951301.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2007810559?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur" href="/user/show/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur">Bryan--Pumpkin Connoisseur</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=boxall-read">boxall-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=books-i-own-and-have-read">books-i-own-and-have-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=books-i-read-in-2019">books-i-read-in-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=new-directions">new-directions</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16951301-bryan--pumpkin-connoisseur?shelf=guardian-read">guardian-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2007810559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9701906378463682412">After recently having read Henry Miller&apos;s <i>Plexus</i>, and now Nathanael West&apos;s <i>Miss Lonelyhearts</i>, it occurs to me that 1930s America is as foreign to me as a colony on one of Jupiter&apos;s moons. I also believe there is a contemporary effort by some to portray the past in terms of today, with the objective of pointing out that people from then were just like people today. In the sense that they had the same emotional urges and drives, I might agree; but when factoring in the pressure of conformity and t</span>
  <span id="freeText9701906378463682412" style="display:none">After recently having read Henry Miller's <i>Plexus</i>, and now Nathanael West's <i>Miss Lonelyhearts</i>, it occurs to me that 1930s America is as foreign to me as a colony on one of Jupiter's moons. I also believe there is a contemporary effort by some to portray the past in terms of today, with the objective of pointing out that people from then were just like people today. In the sense that they had the same emotional urges and drives, I might agree; but when factoring in the pressure of conformity and the relative ignorance of psychology, I think the case can be made that people then were nothing like people now. Of course, some wag writing a hundred years from now will probably say the same thing about us, here in the opening decades of the 21st Century. "What a bunch of maroons!" they might say. <br /><br />I've now read all four of West's novels--I found <i>Balso Snell</i> almost unreadable, <i>A Cool Million</i> sophmorically satirical, <i>Day of the Locust</i> good but not great, and <i>Miss Lonelyhearts</i> fantastic, though fantastically bleak. <i>Miss Lonelyhearts</i> could not be written today, though I don't think it's out-of-date. Strangely enough, it's frank about things that people are too embarassed to write about today. It's the closest thing to Dostoevski that I know of that's come out of America. <br /><br /><i>Day of the Locust</i> verges on the same territory, though it takes a while to get there. Plus, it's too concerned with satirizing the mentality that can create a place like 1930s Hollywood. <br /><br />The characters in both stories seem pschologically alien to me--I think that might put a lot of readers off. And they also reflect attitudes toward women and minorities that are inherently offensive, but in this case, I believe West means us to feel that. Intense and disturbing--readers who are coming to these novels with a conception of Fitzgerald or Hemingway or Frank O'Hara in mind (West's contemporaries) will likely be disappointed; turned-off. West seems to carve out his own ground here.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9701906378463682412" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


