    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2363996425" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2363996425" />
    <a title="Roena" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60069593-roena"><img alt="Roena" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2363996425?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roena" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roena" href="/user/show/60069593-roena">Roena</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2363996425" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15683021291294582624">2-in-1. This book is two stories in one. The broken heart on the front of the book makes fits both stories perfectly. These stories won’t make you cry but they will make you question why you started reading the book. The books slowly drain all the joy and happiness out of you one page at a time. Like most readers I try to connect with the characters in someway but in these that leads you to question the society we live in. Most characters are not a joy to read about. They have a bleak look at li</span>
  <span id="freeText15683021291294582624" style="display:none">2-in-1. This book is two stories in one. The broken heart on the front of the book makes fits both stories perfectly. These stories won’t make you cry but they will make you question why you started reading the book. The books slowly drain all the joy and happiness out of you one page at a time. Like most readers I try to connect with the characters in someway but in these that leads you to question the society we live in. Most characters are not a joy to read about. They have a bleak look at life. Especially in Miss Lonelyhearts, he looks at the world with a cynical view point. He is put in a place where he is constantly questioning his faith and this is what leads to the cynicalness. In The Day of the Locust Tod Hackett looks at the people in Hollywood with a more optimistic point of view, except those that he said, “came to California to die”. Would recommend to everyone I know.<br />In Miss Lonelyhearts the main character is a columnist for a magazine in which he writes the articles for an advice column. Since the story takes place around the time of the Depression, most of the people who write to Miss Lonelyhearts have awful stories to tell and there doesn't seem like they have a lot of hope. This is were Miss Lonelyhearts is suppose to come and give them that hope to cling to. However, Miss Lonelyhearts is someone who needs hope as well. As he struggles with accepting his faith he writes answers to those who need hope even though he has none himself. There is a lovely twist in the bleak tale when it is revealed he got engaged a few months ago and hasn't seen his fiance since. All of these tidbits contribute into a tale of discovery and struggle and also adultery.<br />In The Day of The Locust the main character is an artist hired to paint sets in Hollywood. His name is Tod Hackett and he is an interesting man. He falls for a girl named Faye even though she repeatedly rebuffs him. Similarly to Miss Lonelyhearts, this story isn't about everyone getting a happy ending. This story is more about how there is a thin line between a crush and stalking. This book is also an excellent example of how Hollywood used to be. The way everyone is looking to make it big and how there are depressed people everywhere make this tale a little strange. Especially the way Nathaniel Weinstein creates the characters to be loved and hated at the same time. Depending how you decide to view the story changes the reasoning behind the characters decision. The real reason to read this book is to see another way to view love.<br />The best way to describe my connection with this book is to say the way I felt towards the characters changed from love to hate with each chapter. I would flip from loving one character to hating them the next page. It truly makes you question what you truly love in characters. This book showed me that maybe religion isn't as great as it seems. The Miss Lonelyhearts feels because he doesn't except religion is truly a terrible way to live. It also showed me just how thin the line can become between being a stalker to being someone with a crush. It is truly a scarily thin line. <br />In conclusion, I would recommend to those in the upper grades of high school and who don't take love or religion seriously. The reason I sassy this is because the description of both stories lingers with you. While I didn't mind that because it showed me another way to look at life, it might cause someone to become a littler depressed. Also this book will upset you if you doubt keep an open mind and remember out was written years ago. Overall, I'm glad I read this book even of it made me depressed at times. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15683021291294582624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


